[1] Bat, human exposure - Arizona
Date: 9 Nov 2012
Source: The Arizona Republic and AZ Central [edited]
http://www.azcentral.com/community/mesa/articles/20121109southeast-valley-girl-getting-rabies-vaccine-after-bat-bite-abrk.html?nclick_check=1


A girl in Southeast Valley who was bitten by a rabid bat last weekend is receiving treatment [post exposure prophylaxis, PEP] and is expected to recover, public-health officials said Friday [9 Nov 2012]. The child has been released from a hospital and is undergoing repeated injections of a rabies vaccine [PEP] and immunoglobulin, according to authorities.

This is the 1st confirmed rabid animal in Maricopa County in 2012. Last year, there were 5 confirmed cases according to officials [This is confusing. Were there 5 animal rabies cases or 5 human exposures resulting in post exposure prophylaxis? - Mod.TG].

The most common animals to contract rabies in Arizona are bats, skunks and foxes, according to public health officials. Rabid animals typically show no fear of people or pets and might be active during the day even if they are nocturnal animals.

According to authorities, bats found on the ground, in a pool, or by a pet could be rabid and should be dealt with by an animal-control officer or the Health Department.

Health officials recommend that people avoid feeding and touching wild animals. They also suggest people vaccinate cats and dogs against rabies and avoid sleeping on the open ground while camping.

If somebody is bitten or scratched by any wild animal, they should report it immediately to animal control or a health official, according to authorities.

[Byline: Jonathan Reid]

