[4] Whitetail deer - Minnesota
Date: 5 Nov 2012
Source: Post Bulletin [edited]
http://www.postbulletin.com/news/stories/display.php?id=1514002


When a deer was found nearly drowned in a Mower County pond a few weeks ago, experts thought it might have epizootic hemorrhagic disease, an infectious, sometimes fatal disease that they feared had come into Minnesota from Iowa or some other state.

Much to their surprise, the whitetail had rabies. It was the 1st known case of a whitetail deer with rabies in Minnesota, said Dr. Joni Scheftel, a Minnesota Public Health Department veterinarian.

While it's incredibly rare for a deer to have the disease, "all mammals can get rabies," she said. This one probably got it after being bitten by a rabid skunk. It was not a danger to humans, she said.

The person who reported the deer saw it near a pond and pulled it out. One of the signs of epizootic hemorrhagic disease is that deer seek water because they have a fever, said Dr. Michelle Carstensen, a Department of Natural Resources veterinarian. Another sign is they bleed from the mouth or anus.

The DNR conservation office who was sent to look at it had been alerted to the possibility that epizootic hemorrhagic disease might be coming into the state and went to investigate, Carstensen said. When the animal's brain was tested, it was found to have rabies.

While it's the 1st known case, "it could be that there were cases that went undetected," she said. The other animals, however, might die in the woods, and no one knows it, she said. A rabid animal appears disoriented, acts strangely, and its hind legs become paralyzed.

Having a deer get rabies "is a really good lesson to everyone to vaccinate your dogs and cats for rabies," Scheftel said. They, along with horses [and other livestock - Mod.TG], can get rabies.

Hunters should be reminded to never eat any deer that appears sick. It's just a common safety warning and isn't related to the rabies case, she said.

If hunters see an animal they suspect is sick, it's best to contact a conservation officer, Carstensen said. The officer will decide what to do and could allow the hunter to shoot the animal if it's seen again, she said.

Hunters should also wear gloves when field dressing deer and wash their hands afterward, Scheftel said. Rabies is not found in meat, so it's not a food-safety issue, she said. But there are bugs [microbes] and other things that could be in the entrails of deer that can cause problems for humans, she said.

[Byline: John Weiss]

