[Each of these areas should be scheduling a rabies clinic to insure that pets are vaccinated against rabies. Vaccinated pets often serve as the 1st line of defense against rabies. Pets also include horses and other farm animals. The show calves, goats, and sheep that are part family pet and part show animal are just as susceptible to rabies as other animals. It only takes one rabid bat or skunk to bite the horse or the show calf to expose the children and adults who work with these animals on a daily basis to rabies.

Even the town with the rabid whitetail deer should be considering a vaccination clinic. Having a report of a deer with rabies is unusual and indicates that the disease is in the area and that adequate precautions should be taken.

Human beings that are exposed to rabies need post-exposure prophylaxis. More information on post-exposure prophylaxis for rabies may be found on the CDC website at http://www.cdc.gov/rabies/medical_care/index.html.

Arizona may be found on the interactive ProMED HealthMap at: http://healthmap.org/r/2O9H; New Mexico at: http://healthmap.org/r/2o_v; North Carolina at: http://healthmap.org/r/2M9w; and Minnesota at: http://healthmap.org/r/3eo9. - Mod.TG]
